      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-gray-900">Standing Desk Guide: Manual vs Electric vs Converter — Which to Buy?</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-gray-600">
        Standing desks are not just a trend — they are a health necessity for anyone who works at a computer. Here is how to choose the right one for your body, space, and budget.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 prose prose-lg prose-gray max-w-none">
        <h2>Why You Need to Stand More</h2>
        <p>Prolonged sitting is linked to increased risk of heart disease, diabetes, certain cancers, and back pain. The solution is not standing all day — that causes its own problems. The solution is <strong>movement</strong>. Switching between sitting and standing throughout the day keeps your circulation flowing, engages different muscle groups, and reduces the cumulative strain on your spine.</p>

        <h2>Three Types of Standing Desks</h2>

        <h3>1. Desktop Standing Desk Converters</h3>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> $80-300 | <strong>Best for:</strong> Renters, budget-conscious, people who already have a desk they like</p>
        <p>A converter sits on top of your existing desk and raises your monitor and keyboard to standing height. No need to replace your entire desk. The downside: they take up desk space even when lowered, and they often do not have enough surface area for dual monitor setups.</p>
        <p><strong>Top pick:</strong> VariDesk Pro Plus 36 ($300) — the most popular converter for a reason. Sturdy, smooth spring-assisted lift, works with dual monitors.</p>

        <h3>2. Manual Crank Standing Desks</h3>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> $150-400 | <strong>Best for:</strong> People who stand occasionally, budget-conscious, no power outlet near desk</p>
        <p>A hand crank adjusts the desk height. No motor means no electronics to fail and a lower price. But cranking takes 30-60 seconds each time, and that friction means you will stand less. If you plan to switch positions multiple times a day, go electric.</p>
        <p><strong>Top pick:</strong> IKEA Mittzon ($290) — IKEA's manual standing desk with a clean design and decent build quality.</p>

        <h3>3. Electric Standing Desks</h3>
        <p><strong>Price:</strong> $250-3,000 | <strong>Best for:</strong> Daily standing, multiple users, anyone who wants the best experience</p>
        <p>Press a button, the desk smoothly rises to your preset height. The convenience of electric adjustment means you will actually change positions throughout the day. Memory presets let you save sitting and standing heights. Dual-motor models handle heavier loads and are more stable.</p>
        <p><strong>Top picks:</strong> Flexispot EC1 ($250-300) for value, Uplift V2 ($600-800) for premium, Herman Miller Nevi ($2,000+) for the absolute best.</p>

        <h2>Electric vs Manual: Which Feels Better to Use?</h2>
        <p>This is the real question. Manual crank desks work fine, but every adjustment requires physical effort. When you are in the flow of work and your back starts to feel stiff, "turn a crank for 45 seconds" is a bigger barrier than "press a button." Electric desks reduce the friction to near zero, which means you will actually stand more. If standing is a health priority for you, the extra $100-200 for electric is worth it.</p>

        <h2>Stability: What Actually Matters</h2>
        <p>All standing desks wobble slightly at standing height. More expensive desks wobble less. The factors that affect stability: frame weight (heavier = more stable), column design (inverted columns are more stable than standard), and a crossbar between the legs (adds significant rigidity). If you type heavily or use a monitor arm, invest in a desk with good stability — the Uplift V2 with a crossbar is outstanding in this regard.</p>

        <p>After you get your standing desk, use our <a href="/tools/ergonomic-calculator/">Ergonomic Calculator</a> to find the perfect height settings for both sitting and standing.</p>
